{"cursor":"45493","size":15,"audio":[],"cat":[],"tmpl":[],"currentlang":"en","linknr":506,"url":"Hypatia","article":"\n{{Infobox philosopher |region = Alexandria, Egypt |era = Ancient philosophy\n|color = lightsteelblue |image = |caption = |name = Hypatia () |birth_date = ca.\nAD 351â370 |birth_place = Alexandria |death_date = AD 415 |death_place =\nAlexandria |school_tradition = Neoplatonism |main_interests = Mathematics,\nastronomy |notable_ideas = |influences = Plato, Aristotle and Theon of\nAlexandria |influenced = Synesius of Cyrene }} 'Hypatia' (ca. AD 350â370âMarch\n415) ( ; ; HypatÃ­a) was a Greek Neoplatonist philosopher in Roman Egypt who was\nthe first well-documented woman in mathematics. As head\nof the Platonist school at Alexandria, she also taught philosophy and\nastronomy. Krebs, Groundbreaking Scientific Experiments, Inventions, and\nDiscoveries; The Cambridge Dictionary of Philosophy, 2nd edition, Cambridge\nUniversity Press, 1999:\"Greek Neoplatonist philosopher who lived and taught in\nAlexandria.\" {{Cite book|title= Women of Mathematics: A\nBiobibliographic Sourcebook|last= Mueller|first= I.|authorlink= |coauthors= L.S.\nGrinstein & P.J. Campbell|year= 1987|publisher= Greenwood Press|location= New\nYork|isbn= }} [http://www.bartleby.com/65/hy/Hypatia.html Columbia\nEncyclopedia, Hypatia]{{dead link|date=October 2012}} citation:Alexandrian\nNeoplatonic philosopher and mathematician [http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-\n9041785/Hypatia Hypatia],EncyclopÃ¦dia Britannica:\"Egyptian Neoplatonist\nphilosopher who was the first notable woman in mathematics.\"''\n\nAs a Neoplatonist philosopher, she belonged to the mathematic tradition of the\nAcademy of Athens, as represented by Eudoxus of Cnidus; [http://www.abc.net-\n.au/rn/philosopherszone/stories/2009/2530998.htm#transcript Hypatia of\nAlexandria â a philosophical martyr], The Philosopher's Zone, ABC Radio National\n(4 April 2009). she was of the intellectual school of the 3rd century\nthinker Plotinus, which encouraged logic and mathematical study in place of\nempirical enquiry and strongly encouraged law in place of nature.\n\nAccording to the only contemporary source, Hypatia was murdered by a Christian\nmob after being accused of exacerbating a conflict between two prominent figures\nin Alexandria: the governor Orestes and the Bishop of Alexandria. Edward Jay\nWatts, (2006), [http://books.google.com.br/books?id=0j94OFipg2MC&printsec=frontcover&hl=pt-\nBR&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false City and School in Late\nAntique Athens and Alexandria. \"Hypatia and pagan philosophical culture in the\nlater fourth century\"], pages 197â198. University of California Press\nKathleen Wider proposes that the murder of Hypatia marked the end of Classical\nantiquity, [http://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/3810062?uid=3737664&uid=2-\n&uid=4&sid=21101140085761 \"Women Philosophers in the Ancient Greek World:\nDonning the Mantle\"], by Kathleen Wider. Hypatia Â© 1986 Indiana University Press\np. 49â50; Mangasarian, Mangasar Mugurditch. , 1915 and Stephen Greenblatt\nobserves that her murder \"effectively marked the downfall of Alexandrian\nintellectual life\". Greenblatt, The Swerve: how the world became modern\n2011:93. On the other hand, Maria Dzielska and Christian Wildberg note\nthat Hellenistic philosophy continued to flourish in the 5th and 6th centuries,\nand perhaps until the age of Justinian. Christian Wildberg, in\n[http://www.abc.net.au/rn/philosopherszone/stories/2009/2530998.htm#transcript\nHypatia of Alexandria â a philosophical martyr], The Philosopher's Zone, ABC\nRadio National (4 April 2009); Dzielska 1995, p. 105\n","recorded":1362124389,"portal":[],"list":[],"links":"507","instances":["liturgy","ascetic","philosopher","philosopher","aristarchus","philosopher","philosopher","lexicographer","grammarian","paranormal","philosopher","philosopher","philosopher","moth","mathematician","geometer","prefect","stage_actress","philo